{"title":"Peter Sagan wants to improve your home life","link":"https://cyclingtips.com/2021/03/the-hidden-value-of-peter-sagan-sponsorship-endorsement-deals/","date":1616114658000,"content":"<div id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"><div><p>Although somewhat on the wane as a rider, Peter Sagan still has enduring marketing appeal. Heâ€™s headlined multiple campaigns for Specialized, and attracted endorsement deals for everything from big sunglasses (<a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2020/04/new-for-peter-sagans-face-100s-hypercraft-sunglasses-with-carbon-weave/\">â€œI can see everything I need to!â€</a>) to <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QcyElUBIW8Q\">Jerusalem artichoke extract</a> (Never Forget).&nbsp;</p><p>From a marketing perspective, Peter Sagan has been the most attractive athlete in the sport for a number of years. In 2020, according to <a href=\"https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/peter-sagan-tops-pro-cycling-highest-earners-list/\">Cyclingnews</a>, he was cyclingâ€™s top earner with an income of around â‚¬5.5 million (US$6.55 million)&nbsp;â€“ an amount that incorporates his salary from Bora-Hansgrohe as well as personal endorsement deals.</p><p>Specialized, for example, is widely assumed to have a personal deal with the Slovak star â€“&nbsp;although the brand declined to comment on questions from CyclingTips, citing athlete confidentiality â€“ while 100% sunglasses are almost synonymous with Sagan.</p><p>Saganâ€™s social media presence â€“&nbsp;which includes over 1.8 million followers on Instagram â€“&nbsp;can put a brandâ€™s products in front of a whole lot of eyeballs. A single <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/PeterSagan/videos/10156310387599467/\">viral Peter Sagan Moment</a> in 2018 was estimated by one sports marketing firm to have generated over US$330,000 of value for his sponsors, as <a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2018/04/peter-sagans-330000-facebook-post-and-the-value-of-cyclists-social-media/\">CyclingTips reported</a>.</p><p>And when you multiply that out over all of the Peter Sagan Moments in a season, itâ€™s clear thereâ€™s money to be made.</p><p>Now, expensive bikes and enormous sunglasses are one thing, and advertising these to cyclists is preaching to the choir. But itâ€™s the non-endemic brands that align with Sagan that I, dear reader, find vastly more interesting.</p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1168\" height=\"500\" src=\"data:image/image/jpeg;base64,\" data-src=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/oss_sagan-peter_bora_1899fr-2.jpeg\" alt=\"\" data-srcset=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/oss_sagan-peter_bora_1899fr-2.jpeg 1168w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/oss_sagan-peter_bora_1899fr-2-650x278.jpeg 650w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/oss_sagan-peter_bora_1899fr-2-190x81.jpeg 190w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/oss_sagan-peter_bora_1899fr-2-1080x462.jpeg 1080w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/oss_sagan-peter_bora_1899fr-2-16x7.jpeg 16w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1168px) 100vw, 1168px\"><figcaption>Peter Sagan shows Daniel Oss his sweet potato.</figcaption></figure><p>The German homeware brands that sponsor Saganâ€™s Bora-Hansgrohe team have been particularly creative in capitalising on the Slovakianâ€™s fame. In the process, theyâ€™ve created some of the most arresting brand synergies since <a href=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/2011_Boonen_pillow.jpg\">Tom Boonen had a pillow</a>.</p><p>Bora â€“&nbsp;a cookware specialist â€“&nbsp;has been involved in cycling since 2015, and yesterday released its latest colourful Peter Sagan-starring advertisement for a campaign titled â€œNot Only For Rockstarsâ€. (Peter Sagan is, for whatever itâ€™s worth, not <em>even</em> a rockstar â€“ that Grease clip aside. But sure.)</p><p>In this one-minute spot, Sagan wears headphones and a leather jacket, shreds a town bike down a hill in Monaco to a guitar store, buys a banjolele and butchers John Denver. It is Peak Sagan, following all the familiar beats of his past work: bad boy image &gt; stunt-riding &gt; WTF moment &gt; fade to black.</p><figure><p><iframe title=\"BORA - Not only for rockstars\" width=\"500\" height=\"281\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/IcZqEhamlbk?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe></p></figure><p>Itâ€™s not immediately clear what it <em>is</em> that Boraâ€™s trying to sell â€“&nbsp;I thought it was a waffle iron; itâ€™s actually a futuristic extractor fan â€“&nbsp;but regardless, Bora delivers on the promise of a bit of bicycle-adjacent weirdness that gets the people going.&nbsp;</p><p>Bora isnâ€™t the only German homeware brand to have put Saganâ€™s celebrity to use. Hansgrohe, the luxury sanitary fittings company that has co-sponsored his team since 2017, knows that star power sells showers.</p><p>Hansgroheâ€™s marketing nous is vast and varied. The company knows its way around a hashtag â€“&nbsp;like the <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j9BISHFOFXQ\">Zoolander-esque</a> #MeetTheBeautyOfWater â€“&nbsp;but the real high water mark of its sponsorship was arguably a <a href=\"https://www.petersagan.com/product/petersagan-hand-shower/\">Peter Sagan-branded handshower</a> (limited release, now out of stock ğŸ˜¢).</p><p>The 2019 â€˜<a href=\"https://www.hansgrohe-group.com/en/pressrelease/hansgrohe_tour-de-france_en_2019-07-04\">Shower Like a Pro</a>â€™ campaign had its own peculiar charms; the less said about 2018â€™s <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9IwidvcyA_Y\">â€˜A daily dose of energyâ€™</a> the better, although at least thereâ€™s some symmetry in that itâ€™s a shower ad that makes you feel like you need a shower after watching it.</p><figure><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9IwidvcyA_Y\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"705\" src=\"data:image/image/jpeg;base64,\" data-src=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-18-at-1.29.09-pm-1340x705.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-srcset=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-18-at-1.29.09-pm-1340x705.jpg 1340w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-18-at-1.29.09-pm-650x342.jpg 650w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-18-at-1.29.09-pm-190x100.jpg 190w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-18-at-1.29.09-pm-1080x568.jpg 1080w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-18-at-1.29.09-pm-16x8.jpg 16w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-18-at-1.29.09-pm.jpg 1909w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\"></a><figcaption>Want to watch a selection of supple cyclists have showers in slow motion? Click on that picture, I dare you.</figcaption></figure><p>In 2020, despite Saganâ€™s relative lack of results being a bit of a cold shower, the Slovak and his teammate Emanuel Buchmann were called on to help showcase Hansgroheâ€™s PowderRain feature in a campaign which included the following amazing press release quote:</p><blockquote><p><strong><em>Showering is relaxing, showering is refreshing. This we all know. But hansgrohe wants to take it a step further.</em></strong></p></blockquote><p>This seamlessly segued into a steamy photoset of cyclists enjoying their #MyRelaxingMoment, along with quotes that certainly never happened:</p><figure><ul><div><div><li data-slide-index=\"0\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1172\" height=\"730\" src=\"data:image/image/png;base64,\" data-src=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.37-am.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"501628\" data-srcset=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.37-am.png 1172w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.37-am-650x405.png 650w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.37-am-190x118.png 190w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.37-am-400x250.png 400w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.37-am-1080x673.png 1080w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.37-am-16x10.png 16w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1172px) 100vw, 1172px\"><figcaption>Fact check: false.</figcaption></figure></li></div><div><li data-slide-index=\"1\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1169\" height=\"704\" src=\"data:image/image/png;base64,\" data-src=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.54-am-1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"501682\" data-full-url=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.54-am-1.png\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=501682\" data-srcset=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.54-am-1.png 1169w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.54-am-1-650x391.png 650w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.54-am-1-190x114.png 190w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.54-am-1-1080x650.png 1080w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Screen-Shot-2021-03-16-at-10.47.54-am-1-16x10.png 16w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1169px) 100vw, 1169px\"><figcaption>I do not for a second think that Emanuel Buchmann believes any such thing.</figcaption></figure></li></div></div></ul></figure><p>Regardless of how silly it absolutely all is, the fact that Bora and Hansgrohe have seen fit to spend millions of euro on sponsoring a cycling team â€“&nbsp;and let Peter Sagan fly his freak flag in the process â€“&nbsp;is worth a momentâ€™s pause. Sponsorship is not philanthropy; at this scale, it needs to make a sound financial argument.</p><p>While the exact return is necessarily opaque, there are some hefty clues to how lucrative Peter Sagan is for the brands that align with him.</p><p>In late 2020, Will Bruckbauer, founder and CEO of Bora, announced a lengthy sponsorship extension which will see the cookware company in the sport until at least 2024. â€œFor Bora, the sponsorship was quite the windfall from the very beginning,â€ he said. â€œWe have been conducting regular monitoring since 2015 and have clearly noticed that brand awareness has multiplied, that we are growing much faster and stronger in markets with a connection to cycling, and that the group of people interested in cycling in particular has a much clearer picture of Bora and our products.â€</p><p>The same applies to Hansgrohe, who will be handing out teal boardshorts and creeping on showering cyclists for another four seasons. The companyâ€™s CEO described it as an â€œincredibly successful partnershipâ€ (the team sponsorship, not the showering cyclists + teal boardshorts), saying that â€œthe positive effects on our brand and our consistently pleasant cooperation with the team to this day are factors that have undoubtedly confirmed our decision.â€</p><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1168\" height=\"500\" src=\"data:image/image/jpeg;base64,\" data-src=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/hansgrohe_shower_peter_sagan_249.jpeg\" alt=\"\" data-srcset=\"https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/hansgrohe_shower_peter_sagan_249.jpeg 1168w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/hansgrohe_shower_peter_sagan_249-650x278.jpeg 650w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/hansgrohe_shower_peter_sagan_249-190x81.jpeg 190w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/hansgrohe_shower_peter_sagan_249-1080x462.jpeg 1080w, https://cdn-ctstaging.pressidium.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/hansgrohe_shower_peter_sagan_249-16x7.jpeg 16w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1168px) 100vw, 1168px\"><figcaption>Sagan battles a showerhead in an abandoned factory.</figcaption></figure><p>Although Saganâ€™s sporting dominance may not be what it was, and younger competitors with similar strengths have risen, the enigmatic Slovak remains the sportâ€™s most marketable figure. And if a company hitching its fancy cooktop extractor to his wagon makes a sound financial argument, then itâ€™s a win for cycling. The same goes for <a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2021/03/remco-evenepoel-is-the-face-of-pizza-hut/\">Remco and Pizza Hut</a>, <a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2021/02/watch-watch-whos-rocking-a-hideously-overpriced-timepiece-this-season/\">Richard Milleâ€™s ugly watches</a>, <a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2019/05/what-does-ineos-have-to-gain-by-sponsoring-a-cycling-team/\">Ineosâ€™ petrochemicals</a> and derivative 4WDs, and the <a href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2019/02/the-weekly-spin-the-intersection-of-pro-cycling-and-basic-human-rights/\">human rights-flouting Bahrain and United Arab Emirates</a>.</p><p>OK, perhaps not all of those.</p><p>But in this complicated world, at least you can buy a sensual shower head and live your best life, and in the process be a little bit more like cyclingâ€™s greatest entertainer.</p><div><h5>Tags</h5></div></div></div>","author":"Iain Treloar","siteTitle":"CyclingTips","siteHash":"30feca30fb3902119bf2da6559e7337232527b61c9abe0a00f5d7543c6aa6c84","entryHash":"09855eeb315a31